{"title_page": "Steam Days", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Steam Days\n| image                = Steam Days.jpg\n| caption              = End title card\n| camera               =\n| picture_format       = [[4:3]]\n| audio_format         =\n| runtime              = 30 min\n| creator              =\n| developer            =\n| executive_producer   = Neil Cameron<br>Peter Walton \n| starring             = [[Miles Kington]]\n| narrated             =\n| composer             = [[Roger Limb]]\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| network              = [[BBC Two]]\n| first_run            =\n| first_aired          = 8 July 1986\n| last_aired           = 12 August 1986\n| num_episodes         = 6\n| list_episodes        =\n| preceded_by          =\n| followed_by          =\n| website              =\n}}\n\n'''''Steam Days''''' is a 1986 [[BBC 2]] television documentary series written and presented by [[Miles Kington]]. Each episode is themed around the history of British [[steam locomotives]] and [[railway]]s, particularly highlighting preserved locomotives operating at the time of its filming.<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1577198/Miles-Kington.html Obituary: Miles Kington]\", ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', 1 February 2008</ref> The series consists of six half-hour episodes. It aired on [[PBS|Public Television]] stations in the United States under the title '''''Great Steam Trains'''''. Two episodes, \"Going Great Western\" and \"The Fishing Line\" are available to watch on the BBC Archive website.<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/steamtrains/7317.shtml Going Great Western]\", BBC Archive, ''bbc.co.uk''</ref><ref>\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/steamtrains/7314.shtml The Fishing Line]\", BBC Archive, ''bbc.co.uk''</ref> The whole series subsequently became available to watch on the BBC iPlayer.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00dzmv3/episodes/guide Episodes], BBC Programmes, bbc.co.uk</ref> but until 8 December 2017 and is currently not available.\n\n==Episode list==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Episode No.''' || '''Episode Title''' || '''UK Broadcast Date''' || '''Description'''\n|-\n|1 || \"Travels with a Duchess\"  || 8 July 1986 || A journey over the [[Settle-Carlisle Railway|Settle to Carlisle Railway]] on ex-[[LMS Princess Coronation Class]] ''[[LMS Princess Coronation Class 6229 Duchess of Hamilton|Duchess of Hamilton]]''. The presenter meets Kim Maylon, the ''Duchess''{{'}}s custodian at the [[National Railway Museum]] in York for the engine's preparation for its epic trip.\n|-\n|2 || \"The Fishing Line\" || 15 July 1986 || Miles Kington takes an [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]] [[LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0 44767|\"Black Five\"]] from [[Fort William, Scotland|Fort William]] to [[Mallaig]] on the [[West Highland Line]], examining [[Glenfinnan Viaduct]] and investigating the importance of [[kipper]]s and [[dental drill]]s to the construction of the line.\n|-\n|3 || \"Workhorses\" || 29 July 1986 || Examines the unsung role of [[Freight train|goods engines]] during the age of steam.\n|-\n|4 || \"Quest for Speed\" || 22 July 1986 || Charts the development of the fastest [[Express train|express passenger locomotives]] from the [[GNR Stirling 4-2-2|Stirling Single]] to the [[LNER Class A4]] [[LNER Class A4 4468 Mallard|4468 ''Mallard'']] via the [[GWR 3700 Class]] [[GWR 3700 Class no. 3440 \"City of Truro\"|''City of Truro'']]\n|-\n|5 || \"Going Great Western\" || 5 August 1986 || The history of the [[Great Western Railway]] from the days of [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel|Brunel]] and the [[broad gauge]] \"[[GWR Iron Duke Class|Iron Duke]]\" to the development of the \"[[Cornish Riviera Express|Cornish Riviera]]\".\n|-\n|6 || \"A Tale of Two Scotsmen\" || 12 August 1986 || Explores the history of the \"Flying Scotsman\" - both the [[LNER Class A3]] [[LNER Class A3 4472 Flying Scotsman|4472 ''Flying Scotsman'']] and the [[Flying Scotsman (train)|train of the same name]] running up the [[East Coast Main Line]] from [[London King's Cross railway station|London]] to [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Edinburgh]]. This episode also evaluates the line's many appearances in film.\n|}\n\n==VHS releases==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!#!!VHS name!!Release date!!Episode story\n|-\n|1|| Travels with a Duchess ||  11 October 1986 || Includes: Travels with a Duchess, and The Fishing Line.\n|-\n|2|| Workhorses ||6 January 1987|| Includes: Workhorses, and Going Great Western.\nDespite a third volume being advertised on the end of the second release, it was never released.\n|}\n\n==DVD releases==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!#!!DVD name!!Release date!!Episode story\n|-\n|1|| ''Legends of Steam: The Flying Scotsman'' ||  7 January 2004 || Includes: A Tale of Two Scotsmen.\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|id=1309403|title=Steamy Days}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00dzmv3/episodes/guide Complete series] at BBC Programmes\n* ''[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/series/13861 Steam Days]'' at the [[British Film Institute]]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1986 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1986 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s British documentary television series]]\n[[Category:BBC television documentaries]]\n[[Category:British travel television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Steam Days\n| image                = Steam Days.jpg\n| caption              = End title card\n| camera               =\n| picture_format       = [[4:3]]\n| audio_format         =\n| runtime              = 30 min\n| creator              =\n| developer            =\n| executive_producer   = Neil Cameron<br>Peter Walton \n| starring             = [[Miles Kington]]\n| narrated             =\n| composer             = [[Roger Limb]]\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| network              = [[BBC Two]]\n| first_run            =\n| first_aired          = 8 July 1986\n| last_aired           = 12 August 1986\n| num_episodes         = 6\n| list_episodes        =\n| preceded_by          =\n| followed_by          =\n| website              =\n}}\n\n'''''Steam Days''''' is a 1986 [[BBC 2]] television documentary series written and presented by [[Miles Kington]]. Each episode is themed around the history of British [[steam locomotives]] and [[railway]]s, particularly highlighting preserved locomotives operating at the time of its filming.<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1577198/Miles-Kington.html Obituary: Miles Kington]\", ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', 1 February 2008</ref> The series consists of six half-hour episodes. It aired on [[PBS|Public Television]] stations in the United States under the title '''''Great Steam Trains'''''. Two episodes, \"Going Great Western\" and \"The Fishing Line\" are available to watch on the BBC Archive website.<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/steamtrains/7317.shtml Going Great Western]\", BBC Archive, ''bbc.co.uk''</ref><ref>\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/steamtrains/7314.shtml The Fishing Line]\", BBC Archive, ''bbc.co.uk''</ref> The whole series subsequently became available to watch on the BBC iPlayer.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00dzmv3/episodes/guide Episodes], BBC Programmes, bbc.co.uk</ref> but until 8 December 2017 and is currently not available.\n\n==Episode list==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Episode No.''' || '''Episode Title''' || '''UK Broadcast Date''' || '''Description'''\n|-\n|1 || \"Travels with a Duchess\"  || 8 July 1986 || A journey over the [[Settle-Carlisle Railway|Settle to Carlisle Railway]] on ex-[[LMS Princess Coronation Class]] ''[[LMS Princess Coronation Class 6229 Duchess of Hamilton|Duchess of Hamilton]]''. The presenter meets Kim Maylon, the ''Duchess''{{'}}s custodian at the [[National Railway Museum]] in York for the engine's preparation for its epic trip.\n|-\n|2 || \"The Fishing Line\" || 15 July 1986 || Miles Kington takes an [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]] [[LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0 44767|\"Black Five\"]] from [[Fort William, Scotland|Fort William]] to [[Mallaig]] on the [[West Highland Line]], examining [[Glenfinnan Viaduct]] and investigating the importance of [[kipper]]s and [[dental drill]]s to the construction of the line.\n|-\n|3 || \"Workhorses\" || 29 July 1986 || Examines the unsung role of [[Freight train|goods engines]] during the age of steam.\n|-\n|4 || \"Quest for Speed\" || 22 July 1986 || Charts the development of the fastest [[Express train|express passenger locomotives]] from the [[GNR Stirling 4-2-2|Stirling Single]] to the [[LNER Class A4]] [[LNER Class A4 4468 Mallard|4468 ''Mallard'']] via the [[GWR 3700 Class]] [[GWR 3700 Class no. 3440 \"City of Truro\"|''City of Truro'']]\n|-\n|5 || \"Going Great Western\" || 5 August 1986 || The history of the [[Great Western Railway]] from the days of [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel|Brunel]] and the [[broad gauge]] \"[[GWR Iron Duke Class|Iron Duke]]\" to the development of the \"[[Cornish Riviera Express|Cornish Riviera]]\".\n|-\n|6 || \"A Tale of Two Scotsmen\" || 12 August 1986 || Explores the history of the \"Flying Scotsman\" - both the [[LNER Class A3]] [[LNER Class A3 4472 Flying Scotsman|4472 ''Flying Scotsman'']] and the [[Flying Scotsman (train)|train of the same name]] running up the [[East Coast Main Line]] from [[London King's Cross railway station|London]] to [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Edinburgh]]. This episode also evaluates the line's many appearances in film.\n|}\n\n==VHS releases==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!#!!VHS name!!Release date!!Episode story\n|-\n|1|| Travels with a Duchess ||  11 October, 1986 || Includes: Travels with a Duchess, and The Fishing Line.\n|-\n|2|| Workhorses ||6 January